		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thevoiceswithin.com/?p=134</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[&#8220;What&#8217;s the color of love?&#8217; I ask &#8220;White&#8221; you say, with a flashing grin. &#8220;White is omniscient. It contains all and is contained in all&#8221;. First point in your favor. &#8220;What&#8217;s the color of Life?&#8221; &#8220;Gray&#8221; you say &#8220;something that has no opposites or is its own opposite in the light spectrum&#8221; I sigh. You [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/coppertane/278988858/sizes/l/in/photostream/"><img class="aligncenter" title="Colors" src="http://farm1.static.flickr.com/81/278988858_1851bb220c_b.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="683" /></a></p>
<p>&#8220;What&#8217;s the color of love?&#8217; I ask<br />
&#8220;White&#8221; you say, with a flashing grin.<br />
&#8220;White is omniscient. It contains all and is contained in all&#8221;.<br />
First point in your favor.</p>
<p>&#8220;What&#8217;s the color of Life?&#8221;<br />
&#8220;Gray&#8221; you say<br />
&#8220;something that has no opposites or is its own opposite in the light spectrum&#8221;<br />
I sigh. You look amused.</p>
<p>&#8220;Color of an emotion?&#8217; I ask<br />
Wondering if you&#8217;ll pull this one through.<br />
Pat comes the reply: &#8220;Red. Want me to explain, kid?&#8221; you tease, while I remain silent with indignation.<br />
&#8220;Red is not by itself standardized. An emotion carries the color of the person who identifies with it and eventually &#8216;becomes&#8217; it.&#8221;</p>
<p>You don&#8217;t fail to notice the twinkle in my eyes<br />
when I ask &#8220;What&#8217;s the color of a question?&#8221;<br />
&#8220;What&#8217;s the color of your questions?&#8221; you repeat, emphasizing the &#8220;your&#8221; with a wicked grin.<br />
&#8220;Black since they are either completely dumb or mindbogglingly intelligent&#8221;.<br />
Aware of the apparent confusion you&#8217;ve caused, you add<br />
&#8220;black can be either looked as the lack of all colors or the exhaustive combination of multiple colors&#8221;.<br />
You score. However technically wrong you might be, Mister.<br />
I am nailed. Almost, I mean.</p>
<p>&#8220;What&#8217;s the color of me?&#8221; I whisper<br />
and a strange silence follows.<br />
I think I have you cornered<br />
when you slowly say &#8220;Colors are for the senses, not for the soul&#8221;.</p>
<p>I lose.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
