		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thevoiceswithin.com/?p=116</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The Painted Veil is one of those brilliant movies that satiates your never-ending thirst for questions on romantic fulfillment, the seeds of which haven&#8217;t started sprouting in the dry, barren land the society is, today; sown indeed are the seeds by Prakriti who aspires to fulfill Her own communion with Purusha, a game of eternal [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The Painted Veil is one of those brilliant movies that satiates your never-ending thirst for questions on romantic fulfillment, the seeds of which haven&#8217;t started sprouting in the dry, barren land the society is, today; sown indeed are the seeds by Prakriti who aspires to fulfill Her own communion with Purusha, a game of eternal lila acting as a convenient ruse. Suffice it to say that once the ground allows the water called freedom to permeate, the seeds will do the rest, form the play. The connection is brought out amazingly in the movie, an adaptation of Somerset Maugham&#8217;s book which goes by the same name.</p>
<p>Filled with contempt for her overly criticizing mother who urges her to marry, Kitty Garstin marries Dr. Walter Fane, a bacteriologist working on infectious diseases in China,  not for love, but for the sake of entering the social institution to shut her mother and stay away from her authoritarian ways. Little does vivacious Kitty Garstin know the intricacies of  married life with a serious, socially awkward man like Fane; the non-existent social life in the small Chinese village dooms her idea of romantic love and most of all, freedom. Soon she enters a clandestine affair with Charles Townsend, a married British vice consul. When Fane finds out about Kitty&#8217;s infidelity, he wants her to accompany him to a remote village in China that is infected with cholera. He would divorce her on the grounds of adultery if she doesn&#8217;t accompany him, so she is told. Also, she may leave him if Townsend accepts to divorce his wife and marry her. She immediately proposes the idea to Townsend hoping he would desert his wife for her, only to be rejected by him. She reluctantly agrees to accompany Fane, now that her only hope has been cruelly abandoned.</p>
<p>The idea of a moribund relationship isn&#8217;t appealing to both Fane and Kitty, who sail through the waters of marriage through empty hopes and vain expectations. Fane sees her as an unfaithful, self-centered partner who has ruined both their lives. Plagued by the empty life she leads with Fane, Kitty tries to contact Townsend but is discouraged and disillusioned by Waddington, their only neighbor who subjects her to shocking revelations about Townsend;s promiscuous ways.</p>
<p>There comes a time when both discover themselves slowly yet unfailingly (thanks to the orphanage Kitty willingly offers her services to out of boredom) by starting to see from the other&#8217;s point of view and appreciating the other person for what he/she is. When their recognition of each other blossoms into a new-found love, Kitty finds that she is pregnant but is not sure who the father is. Fane tells her it doesn&#8217;t really matter. He contracts Cholera while trying to help the patients and dies while being nursed by her to the end, making her realize that love doesn&#8217;t need a life time to accomplish its goals.</p>
<p>Five years later, Kitty and her son Walter meet Townsend by accident. When Townsend hints at a revival of their relationship, Kitty  discourages him by walking away. When her son inquires about Townsend, she says that he is &#8220;nobody important&#8221;.</p>
<p>What role does freedom play in the story? Even after knowing about his  wife&#8217;s unfaithful activities, Fane doesn&#8217;t make a fuss out of their  relationship. She abuses the freedom he gives her, no doubt, but it is  this freedom that made her who she became in the end.It is the  responsibility gained from the freedom that made her take a mental  decision.</p>
<p>I am told that the book has a different ending which I, by all means, wish to ignore. The movie portrays a woman who finds the idea of succumbing to Townsend&#8217;s charms disgusting even when there was no one to stop her from appreciating the infidel&#8217;s charms. With Fane dead, she could easily have rekindled the affair. Only she chose not to. It is this very act that takes her to closer to the realms of romance.  The paths she traverses to transform herself is highly commendable.</p>
<p>There is no denying the fact that life teaches us lessons the hard  way to make us more conscious of the choices we have yet remain  conveniently ignorant of. Or put in another way, we remain indifferent  to our own lives by choosing not to exercise the divine rights we  possess.</p>
<p>When will we unveil the veil of ignorance, the bar to finding harmony with ourselves?</p>
