		<description><![CDATA[Sophistication and decency are veils that hide elements deep within us we take the time to suppress. Negative feelings or thoughts aren&#8217;t destructive by themselves; it&#8217;s we who give a whole new shape to them and let them rule our lives. Many a time I have found myself saying that &#8220;I can&#8217;t help thinking about [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Sophistication and decency are veils that hide elements deep within us we take the time to suppress. Negative feelings or thoughts aren&#8217;t destructive by themselves; it&#8217;s we who give a whole new shape to them and let them rule our lives. Many a time I have found myself saying that &#8220;I can&#8217;t help thinking about it&#8221; or questioning &#8220;How can this have happened to me when I did absolutely nothing to deserve it?&#8221; The more the mind dwells on such useless thoughts, the more self-righteous and prejudiced I noticed I became. The &#8220;I&#8221; can never take the blame. It seeks security in other people&#8217;s anger and guilt. More than the act that causes the humiliation or whatever that makes one feel silently furious, it&#8217;s the pride that pricks. It seeks to destroy us and we give it our solemn, gracious permission, calling it &#8220;sophistication&#8221;.</p>
<p>The nineteenth century English aristocrats tried hard to keep up with the trend of masking one&#8217;s true feelings or identity and becoming a victim of the &#8220;true-royal-blood&#8221; syndrome, usually succeeding in it. Anthony Trollope&#8217;s <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_Thorne" target="_blank">Dr Thorne</a> brings this out very well. Augusta Gresham asks her cousin, a De Courcy ( read &#8220;royal blood&#8221;), if she could marry Gazebee, a man she has started to love and her cousin advises her to remember that she is a true blood and that she should keep the pride of the clan by sacrificing such trivial things that might seem like love in the beginning but wither away as time passes. Augusta &#8220;faithfully&#8221; obeys De Courcy&#8217;s orders and rejects Gazebee&#8217;s proposal albeit with a heavy heart. Irony smiles one of her charming smiles when things take a monstrous turn and De Courcy tells Augusta one day that she is to marry Gazebee, the man whom all the De Courcys took a constant liking to. Augusta is flabbergasted but pardons her cousin.</p>
<p>Mary Thorne, a sensible, intelligent girl loves Frank Gresham, who&#8217;s superbly selfish and very very charming. That Mary Thorne is intelligent is undeniable, but why does she choose a man like Frank who&#8217;s no match for her? I felt that she consciously limited her romantic pursuits to Frank; had she aspired for better ideals, she would have ended up marrying a gentleman like Darcy. This is where Mary differs from Elizabeth. Mary had the potential to reveal her great character by virtue of her personality, but she suppressed or limited her aspirations with a vengeance.</p>
<p>This is all we all do to our lives. With a sacred devotion that defies any logic. Be it Mary or Augusta, why are we bound by such nonsensical inhibitions that we are the creators of? I have come to realize over the years that answers don&#8217;t actually matter. Only the questions do.</p>
