		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thevoiceswithin.com/?p=89</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Originally there was only one Veda, and there was no necessity of reading it. People were so intelligent and had such sharp memories that by once hearing from the lips of the spiritual master they would understand. They would immediately grasp the whole purport. But five thousand years ago Vyāsadeva put the Vedas in writing [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote><p>Originally there was only one <em>Veda,</em> and there was no necessity of  reading it. People were so intelligent and had such sharp memories that  by once hearing from the lips of the spiritual master they would  understand. They would immediately grasp the whole purport. But five  thousand years ago Vyāsadeva put the <em>Vedas</em> in writing for the  people in this age, Kali-yuga. He knew that eventually the people would  be short-lived, their memories would be very poor, and their  intelligence would not be very sharp. &#8220;Therefore, let me teach this  Vedic knowledge in writing.&#8221; He divided the <em>Vedas</em> into four: <em>Ṛg,  Sāma, Atharva</em> and <em>Yajur.</em> Then he gave the charge of these <em>Vedas</em> to his different disciples. He then thought of the less intelligent  class of men-<em>strī, śūdra</em> and <em>dvija-bandhu.</em> He considered  the woman class and <em>śūdra</em> class (worker class) and <em>dvija-bandhu.</em> <em>Dvija-bandhu</em> refers to those who are born in a high family but  who are not properly qualified. A man who is born in the family of a <em>brāhmaṇa</em> but is not qualified as a <em>brāhmaṇa</em> is called <em>dvija-bandhu.</em> For these persons he compiled the <em>Mahābhārata,</em> called the  history of India, and the eighteen <em>Purāṇas.</em></p></blockquote>
<p><em>What is Intelligence? Does Ved Vyas mean the buddhi here? English is  a limited language. I was shocked to read the above lines in Sri  Prabhupada&#8217;s <a title="Sri Prabhupada's Commentary on the Isopanishads" href="http://prabhupadabooks.com/d.php?g=156518" target="_blank">commentary on the Isopanishad</a>. He should at least have used the word in brackets. Do we call this negligence? </em></p>
<p><em>Buddhi&#8217;s function is discriminative wisdom which belongs to the higher plane. Intelligence is of the mind which is rooted in Ahamkara. Intelligence is a capacity of the mind while Buddhi is associated with the higher mind. Ironically, the very word &#8216;Buddhi&#8217; is a feminine noun.<br />
</em></p>
<p><em>What I don&#8217;t understand is why the intellectual capacity of the lower classes is undermined when the Vedas say all is One. If we say that the One has manifested as the Many, then how is it possible for one particular sect to be excluded from the category? Is this not an evidence of a streak of egoistic self-righteousness? If something hypocritically sanctimonious like this is spread, how will people know the value of the Vedas? The form stays with the people. Basically, no man sees beyond forms. One minor flaw with the form and he thinks the essence is illusory. Even here, he doesn&#8217;t see the ignorance, the essence. The illusion catches his eye. Illusion is the result of perceived ignorance. </em></p>
]]></content:encoded>
